  "prompt": "Can an L2 visa holder work without EAD?",
  "response": "As of the most recent updates, L-2 visa holders, who are dependents of L-1 visa holders, are generally allowed to work in the United States. Previously, L-2 visa holders were required to apply for and obtain an Employment Authorization Document (EAD) to work legally in the U.S. However, a significant policy change took place in 2021.\n\nWith the updated policy, L-2 spouses of L-1 visa holders are now automatically eligible to work without having to apply for an EAD, provided they have a valid L-2 status. This change was intended to streamline the process and alleviate the burden and delays associated with obtaining an EAD.\n\nHowever, it's important to note that this automatic work authorization does not apply to children on L-2 visas. Also, specific implementation details, such as when proof of EAD-free work authorization might be required by employers, may vary, and it is always advisable for L-2 spouses to consult with an immigration attorney or an official source like the U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS) to ensure they are in full compliance with current regulations and have the necessary documentation to provide to employers.\n\nAdditionally, since immigration policies can change, it\u2019s crucial to verify that these rules are still in place at the time in question.",
